        <p>LEAD:</p>
        <p>Lie Detector for Thornburgh</p>
        <p>Lie Detector for Thornburgh</p>
        <p>The Attorney General took, and passed, a polygraph test during an internal criminal inquiry that led to reassignment of two aides. Page 8.</p>
        <p>Split on Global Warming</p>
        <p>As experts warned that carbon dioxide should be curtailed sharply, Britain broke with the United States by favoring rapid action. Page 6.</p>
        <p>Winnie Mandela Aide Guilty</p>
        <p>A bodyguard of Winnie Mandela, Nelson Mandela's wife, was found guilty of killing a youth who was held at Mrs. Mandela's home. Page 3.</p>
        <p>The Lagging Census</p>
        <p>The second phase of the census, the door-to-door count, is going as badly as the mail-in phase, and it may be extended in New York City. Page 25.</p>
        <p>New York's Right Divided</p>
        <p>New York's Conservative Party has threatened to oppose the Republican choice for governor. Page 25.</p>
        <p>Not Gracie Mansion, but . . .</p>
        <p>Ed Koch, the former Spartan, has decorated his apartment in - surprise! - style. Page 25.</p>
      </block>
